  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Are collagen gummies as effective as powder?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Collagen gummies can be as effective as powder when they deliver at least 2.5g of collagen peptides per serving — matching the dose used in landmark clinical trials. Powder provides higher doses (10-20g), but real-world compliance matters more than theoretical maximum dose. A 2018 survey found 84% of gummy users continue past 90 days vs 32% for powder. For 12+ weeks of consistent daily use, gummies often outperform powder.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Which is better for skin, collagen gummies or powder?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Depends on consistency. Powder (10-20g daily) theoretically produces faster skin results because higher doses accelerate elasticity and hydration improvements. But skin benefits require 12+ weeks of consistent use — and most people stop taking powder within 30 days due to taste or prep hassle. If you will genuinely mix powder into coffee daily for 3 months, powder wins. If you need portable convenience, gummies win because you will actually take them.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How much collagen do gummies have compared to powder?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Collagen gummies typically contain 2.5-5g per serving (2-4 gummies). Collagen powder typically contains 10-20g per scoop. Powders deliver 4-8x more peptides per serving. However, 2.5g is the clinically effective dose established in the 2014 Verisol elasticity trial — so gummies reach the threshold. Higher doses (10g+) show diminishing returns and primarily accelerate results rather than producing fundamentally different outcomes.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Do collagen gummies work as well as pills?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes, when dose-matched. Gummies (2.5-5g) vs capsules (1-3g) — gummies actually deliver MORE collagen per serving than most capsules. Capsules require 4-8 pills daily to match a single gummy serving. The format difference is minimal for absorption because both deliver hydrolyzed peptides. Choose based on preference: gummies for taste, capsules for travel, powder for maximum dose.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How long does it take collagen gummies to work for skin?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Collagen gummies at 2.5g+ daily typically show: hydration improvements at 4 weeks, elasticity gains at 8 weeks, and wrinkle reduction at 12 weeks. A 2014 trial in Skin Pharmacology and Physiology showed 2.5g of Verisol peptides daily produced measurable wrinkle depth reduction after 8 weeks — the same dose and timeline as higher-dose powder studies.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Is collagen powder more expensive than gummies?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Per gram of collagen, powder is 3-5x cheaper than gummies. Vital Proteins powder: $27 for 540g = $0.05 per gram. Vital Proteins gummies: $25 for 30 servings of 2.5g = $0.33 per gram. For clinical doses (5-10g daily), powder costs $0.25-0.50 per day while gummies cost $0.83-1.33 per day. Choose powder if maximizing dose-per-dollar; gummies if prioritizing convenience.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Can you get enough collagen from gummies alone?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes for most skin goals. 2.5-5g daily from gummies meets the clinical threshold for elasticity, hydration, and wrinkle reduction. If your goal is joint support or post-workout recovery, you may want higher doses (10g+) which typically require powder. For anti-aging skin benefits, gummies at 2-4 per day are sufficient.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Do gummies have less collagen because of sugar?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'No — the dose listed on the label is the actual collagen content. However, gummies do contain added sugar (typically 2-4g per serving) and gelatin or pectin bases. If you want collagen without added sugar, look for sugar-free gummies (Transparent Labs, SmartyPants) or switch to powder. The sugar content is not nutritionally significant for most adults but matters if you are diabetic or on a ketogenic diet.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Which tastes better, collagen gummies or powder?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Gummies win taste by a wide margin. Most collagen gummies use fruit flavors (berry, orange, peach) and taste like candy. Unflavored collagen powder is fine in coffee or smoothies but has a slight beefy or marine aftertaste when mixed in water. Flavored powders (chocolate, vanilla) mask the taste but add artificial sweeteners. If taste is your top concern, gummies are the clear winner.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Should I take both gummies and powder?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Generally unnecessary. 5-10g daily is the effective ceiling for skin benefits — most people can get this from either gummies (4 gummies at 2.5g each) or a single powder scoop (10g). Combining both wastes money unless you have a specific reason (extremely high collagen needs from athletes or post-surgical recovery). Pick one format based on your lifestyle and commit to it for 12+ weeks.' } },
  ],
};
