    <h2 id="faq">FAQ: Collagen Gummies vs Powder</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are collagen gummies as effective as powder?</summary><p>Yes at 2.5g+ per serving. Real-world compliance often makes gummies more effective long-term.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Which is better for skin?</summary><p>Gummies win for most people (compliance). Powder wins if you'll actually take it daily.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much collagen in each?</summary><p>Gummies 2.5-5g; powder 10-20g. Clinical threshold is 2.5g daily — both exceed it.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do gummies work as well as pills?</summary><p>Yes — gummies often deliver MORE collagen than capsules (2.5g vs 1-3g).</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long for gummies to work?</summary><p>Hydration 4 weeks, elasticity 8 weeks, wrinkles 12 weeks. Same as higher-dose powders.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Is powder cheaper?</summary><p>Yes — 3-5x cheaper per gram of collagen. $0.05 vs $0.33 per gram typical.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Enough collagen from gummies alone?</summary><p>Yes for skin goals. May need powder for joint or athletic recovery purposes.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Gummies have less collagen due to sugar?</summary><p>No — label dose is accurate. But gummies do contain 2-4g added sugar per serving.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Which tastes better?</summary><p>Gummies (candy-like). Unflavored powder has mild aftertaste in water.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Should I take both?</summary><p>Unnecessary. 5-10g daily is the effective ceiling. Pick one and commit 12+ weeks.</p></details>

